# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alaska-purchase
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] The **1864 National Union National Convention** was the United States presidential nominating convention of the National Union Party, which met in Baltimore, Maryland on June 7 and 8, 1864.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] National Union was the name adopted by the main faction of the Republican Party in a coalition with many, if not most, War Democrats and Unconditional Unionists after some Republicans and War Democrats nominated John C.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] Frémont over Lincoln a few weeks earlier.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] The National Union renominated Abraham Lincoln for president and Andrew Johnson was nominated for vice president.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] During the convention, the party adopted a platform calling for a victorious end in the ongoing Civil War, the eradication of slavery by constitutional amendment and the enforcement of the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] The party name was created in May 1864, during the Civil War, ahead of the 1864 presidential election, in which President Abraham Lincoln, then a Republican, was running for reelection.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] Frémont, who had been the Republicans' first presidential nominee during the 1856 election.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] It was hoped that this act would cause someone other than Lincoln to gain the Republican nomination.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] Republicans loyal to Lincoln created a new name for their party at the convention in Baltimore, Maryland, during the first week in June 1864, in order to accommodate the War Democrats who supported the war and wished to separate themselves from the Copperheads.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] The convention dropped then-Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, a Radical Republican from the ticket, and chose War Democrat Andrew Johnson as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] The National Unionists hoped that the new party and the Lincoln–Johnson ticket would stress the national character of the war.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] The party supported a Platform of 11 resolutions.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] Dennis Francis Murphy, member of the Official Corps of Reporters for the U.S.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] On the first ballot, Missouri delegates cast their 22 votes for General Ulysses S.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] The Missourians quickly changed their votes to make Lincoln's renomination unanimous.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] Though Hamlin was willing to serve another term as vice president, he privately made it known that he was willing to step aside if a candidate who would be a greater electoral asset to Lincoln could be found.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] The convention therefore nominated Andrew Johnson, the military governor of Tennessee.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] Lincoln had refused to weigh in on his preferred running mate, and the convention chose to nominate Johnson, a Southern War Democrat, in order to boost the party's appeal to Unionists of both parties.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-national-union-national-convention] In keeping with the tradition of the time, Lincoln did not attend the convention.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 8, 1864, near the end of the American Civil War.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President Abraham Lincoln of the National Union Party easily defeated the Democratic nominee, former General George B.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, by a wide margin of 212–21 in the electoral college, with 55% of the popular vote.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For the election, the Republican Party and some Democrats created the National Union Party, especially to attract War Democrats.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite some intra-party opposition from Salmon Chase and the Radical Republicans, Lincoln won his party's nomination at the 1864 National Union National Convention.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Rather than re-nominate Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, the convention selected Andrew Johnson of Tennessee, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats were divided between the Copperheads, who favored immediate peace with the Confederacy, and War Democrats, who supported the war.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 Democratic National Convention nominated McClellan, a War Democrat, but adopted a platform advocating peace with the Confederacy, which McClellan rejected, although his running mate George H.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] While the Confederacy seemed to have survival potential in summer 1864, it was visibly collapsing by election day in November.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite his early fears of defeat, Lincoln won strong majorities in the popular and electoral vote, partly as a result of the recent Union victory at the Battle of Atlanta.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War was still raging, no electoral votes were counted from any of the eleven southern states that had joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's re-election ensured that he would preside over the successful conclusion of the Civil War.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's victory made him the first president to win re-election since Andrew Jackson in 1832, as well as the first Northern president to ever win re-election.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was assassinated six weeks into his second term.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was succeeded by his vice president, Andrew Johnson, who favored quick restoration of the seceded states to the Union without protection for the former slaves.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This led to conflict with the Republican-dominated Congress, culminating in Johnson's impeachment by the House of Representatives in 1868; he was acquitted in the Senate by one vote.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election took place during the American Civil War.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] According to the Miller Center for the study of the presidency, the election was noteworthy for occurring at all, an unprecedented democratic exercise in the midst of a civil war.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Republican dissidents who called themselves Radical Republicans formed a party named the Radical Democratic Party and nominated John C.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont as their candidate for president.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont later withdrew and endorsed Lincoln.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] War Democrats joined with Republicans as the National Union Party, with Lincoln at the head of the ticket.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The National Union Party was a temporary name used to attract War Democrats and Southern Border State Unionists who would not vote for the Republican Party.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It faced off against the regular Democratic Party, including Peace Democrats.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election conventions of the parties are considered below in order of the party's popular vote.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War progressed, political opinions within the Republican Party began to diverge.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Senators Charles Sumner and Henry Wilson from Massachusetts wanted the Republican Party to advocate constitutional amendments to prohibit slavery and guarantee racial equality before the law.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Initially, not all northern Republicans supported such measures.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic leaders hoped that the radical Republicans would put forth their own ticket in the election.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* newspaper, particularly interested in undermining the National Union Party, ran a series of articles predicting a delay for the National Union Convention until late in 1864 to allow Frémont time to collect delegates to win the nomination.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont supporters in New York City established a newspaper called the *New Nation*, which declared in one of its initial issues that the National Union Convention would be a "nonentity".
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* also published false information (further purported by Samuel S.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Before the election, some War Democrats joined the Republicans to form the National Union Party.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With the outcome of the Civil War still in doubt, some political leaders, including Salmon P.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase, Benjamin Wade, and Horace Greeley, opposed Lincoln's re-nomination on the grounds that he could not win.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase himself became the only candidate to contest Lincoln's re-nomination actively, but he withdrew in March when a slew of Republican officials, including some within the state of Ohio upon whom Chase's campaign depended, endorsed Lincoln for re-nomination.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was still popular with most members of the Republican Party, and the National Union Party nominated him for a second term as president at their convention in Baltimore, Maryland, on June 7–8, 1864.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent vice president Hannibal Hamlin remaining indifferent about the prospect of a second term in office, Andrew Johnson, the former senator from and current military governor of Tennessee, was named as Lincoln's vice presidential running-mate.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He had been governor of Tennessee from 1853 to 1857 and was elected by the legislature to the Senate in 1857.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his congressional service, he sought passage of the Homestead Bill which was enacted soon after he left his Senate seat in 1862.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] When the Southern slave states, including Tennessee, seceded, he remained firmly with the Union.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was the only sitting senator from a Confederate state who did not resign his seat upon learning of his state's secession.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1862, Lincoln appointed him as military governor of Tennessee after most of it had been retaken.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1864, Johnson was a logical choice as running mate for Lincoln, who wished to send a message of national unity in his re-election campaign, especially to ensure the electoral votes of the border states.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Others who were considered for the nomination, at one point or another, were former Senator Daniel Dickinson, Major General Benjamin Butler, Major General William Rosecrans, Joseph Holt, and former Treasury Secretary and Senator John Dix.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party was bitterly split between War Democrats and Peace Democrats, a group further divided among competing factions.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Moderate Peace Democrats who supported the war against the Confederacy, such as Horatio Seymour, were preaching the wisdom of a negotiated peace.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After the Union victory at the Battle of Gettysburg in 1863, moderate Peace Democrats proposed a negotiated peace that would secure Union victory.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They believed this was the best course of action, because an armistice could finish the war without devastating the South.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Radical Peace Democrats known as Copperheads, such as Thomas H.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Seymour, declared the war to be a failure and favored an immediate end to hostilities without securing Union victory.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan vied for the presidential nomination.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, friends of Horatio Seymour insisted on placing his name before the convention, which was held in Chicago, Illinois, on August 29–31, 1864.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] But on the day before the organization of that body, Horatio Seymour announced positively that he would not be a candidate.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Since the Democrats were divided by issues of war and peace, they sought a strong candidate who could unify the party.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The compromise was to nominate pro-war General George B.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan for president and anti-war Representative George H.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, a War Democrat, was nominated for president over the Copperhead Thomas H.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Pendleton, a close associate of the Copperhead Clement Vallandigham, balanced the ticket, since he was known for having strongly opposed the Union war effort.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention adopted a peace platform – a platform McClellan personally rejected.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan supported the continuation of the war and restoration of the Union, but the party platform, written by Vallandigham, opposed this position.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Radical Democratic Convention assembled in Ohio with delegates arriving on May 29, 1864.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] *The New York Times* reported that the hall which the convention organizers had planned to use had been double-booked by an opera troupe.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Almost all delegates were instructed to support Frémont, with a major exception being the New York delegation, which was composed of War Democrats who supported Ulysses S.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Various estimates of the number of delegates were reported in the press; *The New York Times* reported 156 delegates, but the number generally reported elsewhere was 350 delegates.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates came from 15 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They adopted the name Radical Democratic Party.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A supporter of Grant was appointed chairman.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The platform was passed with little discussion, and a series of resolutions that bogged down the convention proceedings were voted down decisively.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention nominated Frémont for president, and he accepted the nomination on June 4, 1864.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his letter, he stated that he would step aside if the National Union Convention would nominate someone other than Lincoln for president.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] John Cochrane was nominated for vice president.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 election was the first time since 1812 that a presidential election took place during a war.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For much of 1864, Lincoln himself believed he had little chance of being re-elected.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Confederate forces had triumphed at the Battle of Mansfield, the Battle of Cold Harbor, the Battle of Brices Cross Roads, the Battle of Kennesaw Mountain and the Battle of the Crater.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In addition, the war was continuing to take a very high toll in terms of casualties with campaigns such as Grant's Overland Campaign and the perceived lack of progress.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The prospect of a long and bloody war started to make the idea of "peace at all cost" offered by the Ultra Peace Democrats look more desirable.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] However, several political and military events eventually made Lincoln's re-election inevitable.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the first place, the Democrats had to confront the severe internal strains within their party at the Democratic National Convention.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The political compromises made at the Democratic National Convention were contradictory and made McClellan's efforts to campaign seem inconsistent.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Secondly, the Democratic National Convention influenced Frémont's campaign.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont was appalled at the Democratic platform, which he described as "union with slavery".
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After three weeks of discussions with Cochrane and his supporters, Frémont withdrew from the race in September 1864.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his statement, Frémont declared that winning the Civil War was too important to divide the Republican vote.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Although he still felt that Lincoln was not going far enough, the defeat of McClellan was of the greatest necessity.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] General Cochrane, who was a War Democrat, agreed and withdrew with Frémont.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] On September 23, 1864, Frémont also brokered a political deal in which Lincoln removed U.S.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Postmaster General Montgomery Blair from office, and on September 24 Abraham Lincoln relieved Blair of his duty as Postmaster General.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan's chances of victory faded after Frémont withdrew from the presidential race.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lastly, with the fall of Atlanta on September 2, there was no longer any question that a Union military victory was inevitable and close at hand.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, the Union Party mobilized the full strength of both the Republicans and the War Democrats under the slogan "Don't change horses in the middle of a stream".
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It was energized as Lincoln made emancipation the central issue, and state Republican parties stressed the perfidy of the Copperheads.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] 24.4% of the voting age population and 76.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The American Civil War was in progress and unfinished during this election.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Because eleven Southern states plus two claimed additional Southern states had declared secession from the Union and formed the Confederate States of America, only twenty-five states participated in the election.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Louisiana and Tennessee had recently been re-captured.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They chose presidential electors, but their votes were rejected by Congress due to having recently seceded from the Union.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Both states had voted for Lincoln, so it would not have changed the result in any case.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Three new states participated for the first time: Kansas, West Virginia, and Nevada.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan won just three states: Kentucky, Delaware, and his home state of New Jersey.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln won in every state he carried in 1860 except New Jersey, and also carried a state won four years earlier by Stephen Douglas (Missouri), one carried by John C.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge (Maryland) and all three newly admitted states (Kansas, Nevada and West Virginia).
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Altogether, 212 electoral votes were counted in Congress for Lincoln – more than enough to win the presidency even if all of the states in rebellion had participated and voted against him.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This would be the last election in which a party nominee won completely different states than the previous nominee, with McClellan flipping Kentucky and New Jersey, while having lost Missouri.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was highly popular with soldiers and they in turn recommended him to their families back home.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The following states allowed soldiers to cast ballots: California, Kansas, Kentucky, Maine, Michigan, Rhode Island, and Wisconsin.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Only soldiers from Kentucky gave McClellan a majority of their votes, and he carried the army vote in the state by a vote of 2,823 (70.3%) to 1,194 (29.7%).
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 1,129 counties making returns, Lincoln won in 728 (64.5%), while McClellan carried 400 (35.4%).
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] One county (0.1%) in Iowa split evenly between Lincoln and McClellan.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election the Republicans won in Maryland until 1896.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] (a) *The states in rebellion did not participate in the election of 1864.* (b) *The 17 electoral votes from Tennessee and Louisiana were rejected.
[src:alaska-purchase/1864-united-states-presidential-election] States in red were won by Republican Abraham Lincoln; states in blue were won by Democrat George B.
[src:alaska-purchase/1865-state-of-the-union-address] The **1865 State of the Union Address** was written by historian George Bancroft and read to the Congress by Robert Johnson, the son and personal secretary of the 17th president of the United States, Andrew Johnson.
[src:alaska-purchase/1865-state-of-the-union-address] According to one historian, "Johnson had sent Bancroft only two suggestions: passages from Thomas Jefferson's inaugural and from a speech by Charles James Fox." The result was generally high-toned and well received.
[src:alaska-purchase/1865-state-of-the-union-address] It was presented to the United States Congress on Monday, December 4, 1865.
[src:alaska-purchase/1865-state-of-the-union-address] The text stated, "Our thoughts next revert to the death of the late President by an act of parricidal treason.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The **1866–67 United States House of Representatives elections** took place between June 4, 1866, and September 6, 1867, to elect the 193 members and seven non-voting delegates of the House of Representatives.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Republican Party retained its majority in the first midterm elections following the end of the American Civil War.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Republicans and Unionists won 147 seats as the National Union Party in elections held in 1864 and 1865.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Following the assassination of Abraham Lincoln, president Andrew Johnson attempted to lead a political realignment that would enable him to seek re-election.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Johnson's supporters held the 1866 National Union Convention at Philadelphia in advance of these elections.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Johnson's handling of Reconstruction, especially his veto of the Civil Rights Act of 1866, split the governing coalition between moderate and radical Republicans, and the president's dwindling conservative allies.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Pro-Johnson Unionists contested these elections as the Conservative Union Party, while Johnson's opponents were called Republicans or Republican Unionists.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Despite the efforts of Johnson's advisors to preserve its independence, the Conservative movement was quickly folded into the Democratic Party, which reemerged as the main opposition to the Republicans in the postwar era.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The elections resulted in a stunning rebuke of the incumbent administration.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Johnson's national speaking tour failed to win over the voting public and seriously damaged the president's reputation.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Republicans from the border states and the Northern United States won over two-thirds of the seats in the lower chamber, more than enough to override a presidential veto.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In Maryland and Missouri, the Republican candidates ran as Radical or Unconditional Unionists.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Democrats won most of the remaining seats, while only two districts (Missouri's 3rd and New York's 6th) chose Conservative representatives.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Of the former Confederate states holding elections in 1866 and 1867, only the representatives from Tennessee were initially seated; a further eight states held elections following their readmission in 1868.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Alabama did not hold elections until 1868 during Reconstruction.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Florida did not hold elections until 1868 during Reconstruction.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Georgia did not hold elections until 1868 during Reconstruction.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Louisiana did not hold elections until 1868 during Reconstruction.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Mississippi did not hold elections until 1868 during Reconstruction.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Nevada held successive elections in 1866 to fill one vacancy in the 38th Congress and elect its representative to the 39th Congress.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] North Carolina did not hold elections until 1868 during Reconstruction.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] South Carolina did not hold elections until 1868 during Reconstruction.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-and-1867-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Wisconsin elected six members of congress on Election Day, November 4, 1866.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] The **National Union Convention** (also known as the **Arm-In-Arm Convention**) was held on August 14–16, 1866, in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] The convention was called in Philadelphia before the midterm elections of 1866, in an attempt to encourage political support for US President Andrew Johnson, who was under attack by both moderate and Radical Republicans.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] Johnson's friends tried to rally support for his lenient pro-South Reconstruction policies.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] Some hoped to create a new political party, but that goal was not realized.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] For their part, Republican-aligned newspapers called it the *Rebel–Johnson convention*, insinuating Johnson's true loyalty was to the Confederacy.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] Delegates gathered at a hastily built temporary structure that was designed to accommodate the several thousand people expected to attend.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] Formally called "the Wigwam," the immense edifice was on Girard Avenue, between 19th and 20th Streets, across from Philadelphia's Girard College.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] About 7000 prominent politicians and activists attended the convention.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] At its opening, representatives from Massachusetts (General Darius Nash Couch) and South Carolina (Governor James Lawrence Orr) paraded arm-in-arm to symbolize national reconciliation and social equity.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] The convention was called to order by US Postmaster General Alexander Randall.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] General (and former New York Governor and Senator) John Adams Dix served as the temporary chairman and Wisconsin Senator James R.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] Doolittle served as permanent convention president.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] In the end, the convention was not successful in unifying the country behind Johnson.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] He launched a speaking tour (known as the "Swing Around the Circle") hoping to regain public and political support.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] On the speaking tour, Johnson at times attacked his Republican opponents with crude and abusive language and on several occasions appeared to have had too much to drink.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] Ultimately, the tour was a disaster for Johnson and emboldened Congress to override him and to impeach him in 1868.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] In an effort to counter the National Union Convention's support for Johnson, a group of Southern Radical Republicans who opposed Johnson's Reconstruction policy organized the Southern Loyalists' Convention, which was held on September 3, 1866 in Philadelphia's Independence Hall.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] The September convention voted on a resolution supporting black suffrage.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] Boreman argued against it as "we did not come here to commit suicide" and that passing the resolution would have them "damned to all eternity".
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] Frederick Douglass, attending the convention despite pleas from Oliver P.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] Morton, was one of two black delegates to the convention and argued for passing the resolution.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] On September 7, delegates to the Southern Loyalists' Convention voted to pass a resolution endorsing universal male suffrage.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-national-union-convention] Clement Vallandigham, a copperhead from Ohio, was elected to the convention but withdrew to avoid disturbing the harmony of the convention.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-state-of-the-union-address] The **1866 State of the Union Address** was given by Andrew Johnson, the 17th president of the United States, on Monday, December 3, 1866.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-state-of-the-union-address] This State of the Union was not a spoken address, but a written one.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-state-of-the-union-address] The Reconstruction Era had begun, and Johnson wanted a policy that pardoned the leaders of the Confederate States of America.
[src:alaska-purchase/1866-state-of-the-union-address] On additional domestic affairs the President mentioned the rapid construction of the transcontinental railroad, with full completion on track and completion of various treaties with Native Americans tribes that were in rebellion at the beginning of the Civil War.
[src:alaska-purchase/1867-state-of-the-union-address] Robert Johnson, Andrew Johnson's son and Secretary to the President of the United States, reported the President's annual message to the U.S.
[src:alaska-purchase/1867-state-of-the-union-address] The text had been leaked to the press early and an investigation of the leak was requested.
[src:alaska-purchase/1867-state-of-the-union-address] According to one newspaper, "Outside of reconstruction there are many good things in it which will meet the hearty approbation of the country.
[src:alaska-purchase/1867-state-of-the-union-address] On the latter he charges home declaring the Congressional scheme of reconstruction a failure and attended with immense expense, that the negroes being slaves one day are not fit for the exercise of suffrage the next, and twits Congress of the late elections.
[src:alaska-purchase/1867-state-of-the-union-address] The President evidently feels his oats this year and is much more defiant than one year ago.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The **Alaska Purchase** was the purchase of Alaska from the Russian Empire by the United States for a sum of $7.2 million in 1867 (equivalent to $132 million in 2024).
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] On May 15 of that year, the United States Senate ratified a bilateral treaty that had been signed on March 30, and American sovereignty became legally effective across the territory on October 18.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] During the first half of the 19th century, Russia had established a colonial presence in parts of North America, but few Russians ever settled in Alaska.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Alexander II of Russia, having faced a catastrophic defeat in the Crimean War, began exploring the possibility of selling the state's Alaskan possessions, which, in any future war, would be difficult to defend from the United Kingdom.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Seward, the U.S. secretary of state at the time, entered into negotiations with Russian diplomat Eduard de Stoeckl towards the United States' acquisition of Alaska after the American Civil War.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Seward and Steckel agreed to a treaty for the sale on March 30, 1867.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Reactions to the Alaska Purchase among Americans were mostly positive, as many believed that Alaska would serve as a base to expand American trade in Asia.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Some opponents labeled the purchase as "**Seward's Folly**" or "**Seward's Icebox**" as they contended that the United States had acquired useless land.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Nearly all Russian settlers left Alaska in the aftermath of the purchase; Alaska would remain sparsely populated until the Klondike Gold Rush began in 1896.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Originally organized as the Department of Alaska, the area was renamed the District of Alaska in 1884 and the Territory of Alaska in 1912, ultimately becoming the modern-day state of Alaska in 1959.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Russian America was settled by *promyshlenniki*, merchants and fur trappers who expanded through Siberia.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] They arrived in Alaska in 1732, and in 1799 the Russian-American Company (RAC) received a charter to hunt for fur.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] No colony was established, but the Russian Orthodox Church sent missionaries to the natives and built churches.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] About 700 Russians enforced sovereignty in a territory over twice as large as Texas.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] In 1821, Tsar Alexander I issued an edict declaring Russia's sovereignty over the North American Pacific coast north of the 51st parallel north.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The edict also forbade foreign ships to approach within 100 Italian miles (115 miles or 185 km) of the Russian claim.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] US secretary of state John Quincy Adams strongly protested the edict, which potentially threatened both the commerce and expansionary ambitions of the United States.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Seeking favorable relations with the U.S., Alexander agreed to the Russo-American Treaty of 1824.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] In the treaty, Russia limited its claims to lands north of parallel 54°40′ north and also agreed to open Russian ports to U.S. ships.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] By the 1850s, a population of once 300,000 sea otters, who were skinned for their valuable fur, was almost extinct, and Russia needed money after being defeated by France and Britain in the Crimean War.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The California gold rush showed that if gold were discovered in Alaska, Americans and Canadians would overwhelm the Russian presence in what one scholar later described as "Siberia's Siberia".
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] However, the principal reason for the sale was that the hard-to-defend colony would be easily conquered by British forces based in neighboring Canada in any future conflict, and Russia did not wish to see its archrival being next door just across the Bering Sea.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Therefore, Emperor Alexander II decided to sell the territory.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The Russian government discussed the proposal in 1857 and 1858 and offered to sell the territory to the United States, hoping that its presence in the region would offset the plans of Britain.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] However, no deal was reached, as the risk of an American Civil War was a more pressing concern in Washington.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Grand Duke Konstantin, a younger brother of the Tsar, began to press for the handover of Russian America to the United States in 1857.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Konstantin's letter was shown to his brother, Tsar Alexander II, who wrote "this idea is worth considering" on the front page.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Supporters of Konstantin's proposal to immediately withdraw from North America included Admiral Yevfimy Putyatin and the Russian minister to the United States, Eduard de Stoeckl.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Gorchakov agreed with the necessity of abandoning Russian America but argued for a gradual process leading to its sale.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] He found a supporter in the naval minister and former chief manager of the Russian-American Company, Ferdinand von Wrangel.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Wrangel pressed for some proceeds to be invested in the economic development of Kamchatka and the Amur Basin.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The Emperor eventually sided with Gorchakov, deciding to postpone negotiations until the end of the RAC's patent, set to expire in 1861.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Over the winter of 1859–1860, Stoeckl held meetings with United States officials, though he had been instructed not to initiate discussions about the sale of the RAC assets.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Communicating primarily with Assistant Secretary of State John Appleton and California senator William M.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Gwin, Stoeckl reported the interest expressed by the Americans in acquiring Russian America.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] While President James Buchanan kept these hearings informal, preparations were made for further negotiations.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Stoeckl reported a conversation in which he asked "in passing" what price the U.S. government might pay for the Russian colony and Senator Gwin replied that they "might go as far as $5,000,000", a figure Gorchakov found far too low.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Stoeckl informed Appleton and Gwin of this, the latter saying that his Congressional colleagues in Oregon and California would support a larger figure.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Buchanan's increasingly unpopular presidency forced the matter to be shelved until a new presidential election.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] With the oncoming American Civil War, Stoeckl proposed a renewal of the RAC's charter.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Two of its ports were to be open to foreign traders and commercial agreements with Peru and Chile to be signed to give "a fresh jolt" to the company.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Russia continued to see an opportunity to weaken British power by causing British Columbia, including the Royal Navy base at Esquimalt, to be surrounded or annexed by American territory.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Following the Union victory in the Civil War in 1865, the Tsar instructed Stoeckl to re-enter into negotiations with William H.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] President Andrew Johnson was busy with negotiations about Reconstruction, and Seward had alienated a number of Republicans, so both men believed that the purchase would help divert attention from domestic issues.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The negotiations concluded after an all-night session with the signing of the treaty at 04:00 on March 30, 1867.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The purchase price was set at $7.2 million (equivalent to $132 million in 2024), or about 2 cents per acre ($4.74/km2).
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Much of the money Russia earned from the sale was reportedly paid to two Americans, Thomas and William Winans from Baltimore, Maryland, who were under contract with the Tsar to build and maintain Russia's railway system.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The Winans were seen as "the robber of the Russian Treasury", contract costs had ballooned exponentially.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The Winans received six and a half million rubles of the Alaskan sale proceeds.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The Russian name for the Alaska Peninsula was *Alyaska* ("Аляска") or *Alyeska*, from an Aleut word, *alashka* or *alaesksu*, meaning "great land" or "mainland".
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The United States chose the name "Alaska" to refer to the area purchased from Russia.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Seward told the nation that, according to Russian estimates, Alaska had about 60,000 inhabitants.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] This included about 10,500 who were under the direct government of the Russian fur company: about 8,000 indigenous people and 2,500 people of Russian or mixed Russian and indigenous descent (for example, having a Russian father and a native mother).
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The remaining 50,000 or so were Inuit or Alaska Natives living outside of Russia's jurisdiction.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Seward also said that the Russians were settled at 23 trading posts, placed on accessible islands and at points along the coast.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] At smaller trading posts, typically only four or five Russians were stationed: their job was to collect furs from the natives for storage and then for shipment when the company's boats arrived to take the furs away.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] One was New Archangel (now named Sitka), established in 1804 to handle the valuable trade in the skins of sea otters; in 1867, it had 116 small log cabins and 968 residents.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Paul, in the Pribilof Islands, which had 100 homes and 283 residents, and was the center of the seal fur industry.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Seward and many other Americans expected that Asia would become an important market for U.S. products, and that Alaska would serve as a base for American trade with Asia and globally, and for the extension of American power into the Pacific.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Senator Charles Sumner, chair of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, sponsored the Senate bill authorizing the U.S. to approve the treaty to acquire the territory.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] He not only agreed about the benefit to trade, but also said he expected the territory to be valuable on its own; having studied the records of explorers, he believed it contained valuable animals and forests.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] He compared the acquisition to contemporary European colonial acquisitions, such as the French conquest of Algeria.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The United States Senate approved the treaty by a vote of 37 to 2.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Many Americans believed in 1867 that the purchase process had been corrupt, but W.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Dall in 1872 wrote that "there can be no doubt that the feelings of a majority of the citizens of the United States are in favor of it." The notion that the purchase was unpopular among Americans is, a scholar wrote 120 years later, "one of the strongest historical myths in American history.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] It persists despite conclusive evidence to the contrary, and the efforts of the best historians to dispel it", likely in part because it fits American and Alaskan writers' view of the territory as distinct and filled with self-reliant pioneers.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] A majority of newspapers either supported the purchase or were neutral.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] A review of dozens of contemporary newspapers found general support for the purchase, especially in California; most of 48 major newspapers supported the purchase.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Public opinion was not universally positive; to some the purchase was known as "Seward's folly", "Walrussia", or "Seward's icebox".
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Editorials contended that taxpayer money had been wasted on a "polar bear garden".
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Forty-five percent of supportive newspapers cited the increased potential for annexing British Columbia in their support, and *The New York Times* stated that, consistent with Seward's reason, Alaska would increase American trade with East Asia.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The principal urban newspaper that opposed the purchase was the *New York Tribune*, published by Seward opponent Horace Greeley.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The ongoing controversy over Reconstruction spread to other acts, including the Alaska purchase.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Some opposed the United States obtaining its first non-contiguous territory, seeing it as a colony; others saw no need to pay for land that they expected the country to obtain through manifest destiny.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The transfer ceremony took place in Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Russian and American soldiers paraded in front of the governor's house; the Russian flag was lowered and the American flag raised amid peals of artillery.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] A description of the events was published in Finland six years later.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] After the flag transition was completed, Captain of 2nd Rank Aleksei Alekseyevich Peshchurov said, "General Rousseau, by authority from His Majesty, the Emperor of Russia, I transfer to the United States the territory of Alaska." General Lovell Rousseau accepted the territory.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] (Peshchurov had been sent to Sitka as commissioner of the Russian government in the transfer of Alaska.) A number of forts, blockhouses and timber buildings were handed over to the Americans.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The troops occupied the barracks; General Jefferson C.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Davis established his residence in the governor's house, and most of the Russian citizens went home, leaving a few traders and priests who chose to remain.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] After the transfer, a number of Russian citizens remained in Sitka, but nearly all of them very soon decided to return to Russia, which was still possible at the expense of the Russian-American Company.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Moreover, Ahllund's article is the only known description of the return voyage on the *Winged Arrow*, a ship that was specially purchased to transport the Russians back to their native country.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] "The over-crowded vessel, with crewmen who got roaring drunk at every port, must have made the voyage a memorable one." Ahllund mentions stops at the Sandwich (Hawaiian) Islands, Tahiti, Brazil, London, and finally Kronstadt, the port for St.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Petersburg, where they arrived on August 28, 1869.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] American settlers who shared Sumner's belief in the riches of Alaska rushed to the territory but found that much capital was required to exploit its resources, many of which could also be found closer to markets in the contiguous United States.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Most soon left, and by 1873, Sitka's population had declined from about 2,500 to a few hundred.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The United States acquired an area over twice as large as Texas, but it was not until the great Klondike Gold Rush in 1896 that Alaska generally came to be seen as a valuable addition to U.S. territory.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The seal fishery was one of the chief considerations that induced the United States to purchase Alaska.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] It provided considerable revenue by the lease of the privilege of taking seals, an amount that was eventually more than the price paid for Alaska.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] From 1870 to 1890, the seal fisheries yielded 100,000 skins a year.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The company to which the administration of the fisheries was entrusted by a lease from the US government paid a rental of $50,000 per annum and in addition thereto $2.62+1⁄2 per skin for the total number taken.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The skins were transported to London to be dressed and prepared for world markets.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The business grew so large that the earnings of English laborers after the acquisition of Alaska by the United States amounted by 1890 to $12,000,000.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] However, exclusive US control of this resource was eventually challenged, and the Bering Sea Controversy resulted when the United States seized over 150 sealing ships flying the British flag, based out of the coast of British Columbia.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The conflict between the United States and Britain was resolved by an arbitration tribunal in 1893.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The waters of the Bering Sea were deemed to be international waters, contrary to the US contention that they were an internal sea.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The US was required to make a payment to Britain, and both nations were required to follow regulations developed to preserve the resource.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] The purchase of Alaska has been referenced as a "bargain basement deal" and as the principal positive accomplishment of the otherwise much-maligned presidency of Andrew Johnson.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Barker has argued that the US federal government has not earned a positive financial return on the purchase of Alaska.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] According to Barker, tax revenue and mineral and energy royalties to the federal government have been less than federal costs of governing Alaska plus interest on the borrowed funds used for the purchase.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Miller has taken the argument further by contending that US oil companies that developed Alaskan petroleum resources did not earn enough profits to compensate for the risks that they incurred.
[src:alaska-purchase/alaska-purchase] Alaska Day is a holiday for all state workers.
